# Memory management overview

This directory is the single source of truth for accepted Beanstalk program memory semantics.

Companion authorities:

- `docs/compiler-design-overview.md` owns compiler-stage and artefact architecture
- `docs/build-system-design.md` owns project, link and builder lifecycle orchestration
- `docs/language-overview.md` and `docs/src/docs/codebase/language/**` own source syntax
- `docs/src/docs/progress/#page.bst` owns current implementation support
- `docs/roadmap/roadmap.md` owns sequencing and deferred implementation order

**Beanstalk is reference-semantic by default, copy-explicit and move-inferred. It omits explicit reference types and lifetime syntax, not references themselves.**

The source language stays small: existing values use shared access by default, mutation requires explicit exclusive access, copies are explicit and moves are inferred by the compiler.

These pages record accepted memory model and target backend architecture. They include design decisions that may not yet be fully implemented, particularly around lifetime-region analysis, grouped memory and ownership-aware Wasm lowering.

They are not an implementation-status report. Use `docs/src/docs/progress/#page.bst` for current support and major gaps.

## The model in one paragraph

Beanstalk is semantically GC-safe and reference-semantic. Existing values use shared, read-only access by default. Mutation requires explicit exclusive access. Copies are explicit, moves are inferred and ownership-aware destruction is an optimisation layered over mandatory borrow validation and mandatory lifetime-topology validation.

If ownership optimisation cannot be proven or is not useful for a backend, the value remains GC-managed without changing program behaviour. GC cannot make an invalid or unproven lifetime topology legal.

## Two proof layers

**Mandatory semantic proof**

- access and exclusivity legality
- alias relationships
- lifetime owner and region legality
- retained-edge outlives relationships
- escape legality
- cycle legality
- external-boundary legality

User-authored topology that is invalid or cannot be proven legal produces a structured `CompilerDiagnostic`. Missing or inconsistent compiler-owned summaries, boundary classifications, lifecycle roots, or metadata produce `CompilerError`.

**Optional optimisation proof**

- final-use transfer
- deterministic drop placement
- retain/drop elimination
- stack, arena or region allocation
- collector elision
- ownership specialisation

Failure to prove an optimisation must preserve semantics through a conservative representation such as GC. It must not reject the program.

Do not treat "ownership unavailable" and "topology unproven" as the same fallback case. Missing optimisation proof may use GC. Missing topology proof is a source diagnostic.

## Rules every contributor must know

**1. Beanstalk is reference-semantic by default.** Reading, binding, passing, returning or storing an existing value uses shared reference semantics unless exclusive access or explicit copy applies. The language omits reference type constructors and lifetime syntax, not references themselves.

**2. Copies are explicit.** `copy` creates an independent value graph. Ordinary assignment and argument passing do not clone existing values. Fresh aggregates built from shared inputs do not implicitly copy those inputs.

**3. `~` requests exclusive access.** `~place` applies to an existing mutable place. It requests temporary mutation-capable access and excludes conflicting access. It is not a move marker or a type identity. Fresh rvalues satisfy ordinary mutable parameters without source `~`. Mutable receivers always require an existing mutable place.

**4. Inferred transfer is optional.** There is no explicit move syntax. The compiler may transfer destruction responsibility only at proven final-use points. When proof is unavailable, the operation remains a borrow. Lack of transfer proof must not reject an otherwise valid program.

**5. Borrow validation is mandatory.** Shared and exclusive conflicts are checked under every backend, including GC-only backends.

**6. One lifetime owner and stored-edge legality.** Every allocation has exactly one semantic lifetime owner. An object may retain a reference only when the referenced allocation belongs to the same lifetime region or to a region statically known to outlive the retaining object (`R_value >= R_container`).

**7. Lifetime-region validation is mandatory.** Lifetime topology is a backend-neutral source-legality check after borrow validation. GC cannot bypass it. Build profiles may vary optional optimisation-analysis effort and physical allocation strategy. They must run semantically equivalent mandatory borrow and lifetime-topology validation and must not change source legality.

**8. Backend representation is optional.** GC, internal RC, arenas, handles, stack storage and hybrid representations may realise a topology already proven legal. Source-visible RC and unrestricted dynamic shared ownership remain outside the language.

## Goals and tradeoffs

- Unconditional memory safety under all backends and profiles.
- A predictable source model without reference types, lifetime syntax or move keywords.
- Stronger static proof improves performance without changing language semantics.
- Conservative topology analysis may reject unproven structures.
- Optional ownership proof may fall back without rejection.
- Runtime checks and collection may remain where optimisation is unavailable.

## Compiler and backend layers

[codeblock, $code("text"):
    source access and copy rules
        -> AST access-mode, placement and freshness validation
        -> validated HIR with explicit places and control flow
        -> borrow validation and optional transfer facts
        -> lifetime-region and escape validation
        -> build-owned reachability, lifecycle roots and target planning
        -> GC, region, ownership-aware or other validated backend lowering
]

Local module compilation produces local lifetime constraints and exported summaries. Project/link analysis instantiates those summaries over the reachable call graph and builder-supplied lifecycle roots. Backends receive a validated topology and may not reconsider source legality.

- AST validates source access syntax, mutable call requirements and explicit copies.
- HIR represents places and control flow explicitly and materialises fresh mutable call arguments where necessary.
- Borrow validation enforces exclusivity, alias safety and optional transfer safety.
- Lifetime-region validation enforces one owner, retained-edge legality, escapes and cycles.
- Backend lowering applies GC, ownership metadata, conditional destruction or specialisation without changing semantics.

